{"id":5506,"date":"2025-12-05T18:42:21","date_gmt":"2025-12-05T15:42:21","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/emuseum.torus.kz\/exhibit\/68da9f2b0f1ce6a8c-en\/"},"modified":"2025-12-31T13:19:36","modified_gmt":"2025-12-31T10:19:36","slug":"68da9f2b0f1ce6a8c-en","status":"publish","type":"exhibit","link":"https:\/\/e-museum.kz\/en\/exhibit\/68da9f2b0f1ce6a8c-en\/","title":{"rendered":"Chest"},"content":{"rendered":"<p>A chest is a type of case furniture with a hinged lid, designed for storing clothing, household items, and valuables. In the traditional culture of the Kazakh people, the chest held not only utilitarian but also symbolic significance &#8212; it was often included in a bride\u2019s dowry.<br \/>\nThe front of this chest is decorated with an intricate national ornament carved in wood. The pattern is symmetrical and incorporates traditional Kazakh geometric and zoomorphic motifs.<br \/>\nOn the sides of the chest are metal handles (maqtabarlar) used for convenient transportation. These metal elements serve both practical and decorative purposes.<br \/>\nThe item is made of wood using traditional techniques such as carving, tapering, and polishing. The surface is carefully finished and polished to highlight the natural texture of the wood.<br \/>\nSuch chests were widely used in the everyday life of Kazakhs and are important examples of folk decorative and applied art.<br \/>\nDating: 2019<br \/>\nRegion: Kazakhstan<br \/>\nMaterials: Wood, metal<br \/>\nManufacturing techniques: Carving, tapering, polishing<br \/>\nDimensions: 62 \u00d7 105 \u00d7 60 cm<br \/>\nReceived into the collection: 2019<\/p>\n","protected":false},"featured_media":0,"menu_order":0,"template":"","meta":{"site-sidebar-layout":"default","site-content-layout":"","ast-site-content-layout":"default","site-content-style":"default","site-sidebar-style":"default","ast-global-header-display":"","ast-banner-title-visibility":"","ast-main-header-display":"","ast-hfb-above-header-display":"","ast-hfb-